  0: '''What is Quantity?
    A quantity is a property of some object or collection of objects that is measurable. A quantity or amount can be compared: one quantity can be greater than, less than, or equal to another quantity. The concept of quantity is used throughout mathematics and the sciences. For example, in comparing the lengths of two unequal line segments, one would say that the quantity of length of one line segment is greater than the quantity of length of the other. When you touch a hot stove, it feels hot because it has a greater quantity of heat than your hand does. Any property which cannot be compared is not a quantity: names are not quantities, neither is the color of my shirt (blue), nor is the property of being a scientist, etc.
    A quantity is usually presented as a product of a magnitude and a unit. For example, the quantity of height of the Empire State Building is 1454 feet. It would take 1454 foot-long rulers to measure the building from the ground to its tip. For collections of objects, each object is taken to be a unit, so we describe a carton of eggs as holding a quantity of 12 eggs.
    Save  Timeline Autoplay  Speed Normal
    Video  Quiz  Course
    36K views
    The Empire State Building.
    Very tall indeed!
    Quantity in Math
    In mathematics, we usually avoid the use of units in describing quantities and generally describe them by just their magnitude or number. This is because the properties and relations that we are investigating and describing in mathematics are abstract and the units are invariant. For example, if a problem asks for the value of quantity x in the equation x + 2 = 4, that x = 2 is the same whether the numbers in the equations are representing dollars, eggs, lightyears, or percentages.
    It is important that when we are working without units that we are careful to take notice of the dimensions that are associated with each quantity. For example, we can calculate the area of a square with a side length of 2 units to be 4 units squared.
    Square with an area of 4.
    The relation between the sides and the area is independent of the units used.
    This is important because we need to understand that 4 - 2, where 4 is the quantity of area and 2 is the quantity of length is nonsense. As a general rule quantities with different dimensions cannot be compared. Comparisons include summation, subtraction, and equality. This distinguishes geometry from arithmetic in general. Geometrical quantities have dimensions, even if they lack units, while arithmetical quantities have no dimensions if they lack units.
    In addition to geometrical quantities, which describe properties of length, area, angle, and volume, arithmetical quantities describe basic properties of magnitude or number. There are also ratio quantities which are described by fractions or percentages. Ratio quantities like 2/5 or 10% describe how two quantities are related. If the quantity of students absent out of the total quantity of students in the class is 10%, then for every nine students in attendance, one student is absent.
    Other Uses for Quantity
    Quantities are used everywhere outside of pure mathematics in both everyday lives and in many sciences. You use quantities when shopping, when counting, when doing calculus, and when remembering your age. Quantities are one of the basic tools we use to think about the world.''',
